# Prime Intellect publish attempt — log

Date: 2026-04-24 (Sprint 1 Task 5.2)

## Steps attempted

1. `pip install prime` — ✅ CLI v0.5.69 installed.
2. `prime --help` — ✅ commands `lab`, `env`, `eval`, `gepa`, `rl`, `deployments`.
3. `prime env --help` — ✅ `push`, `init`, `install`, `list` etc. documented.
4. `prime whoami` — ❌ "No API key configured. Use command 'prime login' to configure your API key."
5. `prime login` — **not run**. Requires a browser-based OAuth flow which the
   automation pipeline cannot complete headlessly. User must sign in at
   https://app.primeintellect.ai/ and run `prime login` once.
6. `prime env push` against `packages/verifiable-labs-sparse-fourier/` —
   ❌ Reports "No environment Python file found. Unexpected error: 1" even
   though the verifiers entry-point is declared in `pyproject.toml`. The CLI
   expects an explicit single-file `environment.py` when `--path` points at a
   bare directory; with our wrapper-subpackage layout we'd want
   `prime env push -p packages` and explicit `ENV_ID` per call. **Not retried
   because auth is required first.**

## Net outcome

- Package split (Task 5.1) ✅ **shipped as primary deliverable**.
- Verifiers entry-points declared in all 6 env `pyproject.toml` files so
  `prime env install <pypi-name>` will resolve the factory automatically
  once published.
- Hub publish itself is **paused pending user action** (`prime login` +
  possibly CLI-side layout tweak). No fake success claimed; the README
  advertises the GitHub-subdirectory install path as canonical.

## What the user needs to do to complete publish

```bash
# One-time setup
prime login                                     # browser OAuth, saves ~/.prime/config

# Per env (six total)
cd packages/verifiable-labs-sparse-fourier
prime env push --plain verifiable-labs-sparse-fourier --visibility PUBLIC
# Repeat for the other five packages.
```

If `prime env push` still reports "No environment Python file found" after
auth, run `prime env init --help` and follow the documented single-file /
multi-file layout — our packages may need a small wrapper adjustment to
match the Hub's expected structure. Open a GitHub issue against the
`PrimeIntellect-ai/verifiers` repo if the CLI rejects a verifiers entry-point
declared via the standard `[project.entry-points."verifiers.environments"]`
mechanism.
